WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.000
Thank you, everyone, for the opportunity to present here today

00:00:04.000 --> 00:00:04.080
.

00:00:04.080 --> 00:00:05.720
I'm very happy to be at the Atmosphere Conference

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:08.180
and at the first AtProto Science Conference and tell you

00:00:08.180 --> 00:00:09.120
about my work.

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:10.420
So I'm Sean Youngbluth.

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:14.160
I'm a researcher at the San Francisco State Estuary Marine

00:00:14.160 --> 00:00:14.840
Science Center.

00:00:14.840 --> 00:00:16.870
I'm an adjunct professor there, and I'm

00:00:16.870 --> 00:00:18.920
a former Berkeley lab transplant.

00:00:18.920 --> 00:00:21.670
I'm a biologist, oceanographer, and computational person

00:00:21.670 --> 00:00:21.890
.

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:24.530
And I'm telling you about BioKia, this company

00:00:24.530 --> 00:00:27.230
that I founded and this first product that we're trying to

00:00:27.230 --> 00:00:28.520
build called Agentis.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:30.300
So what do we do?

00:00:30.300 --> 00:00:33.690
I'm working with a lot of insect enthusiasts, and we

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:37.900
are running around California, and we are sampling all the different

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:40.460
parts, and we are taking it back into the laboratory.

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:43.750
And my group, we have robotics there where we're looking

00:00:43.750 --> 00:00:46.600
at these things in very, very high throughput, cataloging

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:49.490
all the diversity of life that's in California.

00:00:49.500 --> 00:00:54.620
And then I'm leveraging the power of scientific storytelling through L

00:00:54.620 --> 00:00:58.290
LMs and trying to bring all this information to the light

00:00:58.410 --> 00:00:58.610
.

00:00:58.920 --> 00:01:01.420
And so BioKia, the company, is the engine

00:01:01.420 --> 00:01:03.660
, and the product, Agentis, is the output

00:01:03.660 --> 00:01:03.920
.

00:01:03.920 --> 00:01:07.310
So what does a user journey look like here in the context

00:01:07.420 --> 00:01:08.940
of an at-proto connection?

00:01:08.940 --> 00:01:12.830
So the use case is imagining that you have researchers that are

00:01:12.830 --> 00:01:16.290
traveling to the Santa Monica Mountains to sample some dirt and then

00:01:16.290 --> 00:01:19.680
try to understand the scientific life that's inside of it.

00:01:19.680 --> 00:01:23.120
And so first, the folks will ingest the data into

00:01:23.190 --> 00:01:24.220
our system.

00:01:24.380 --> 00:01:26.680
We'll analyze the data using canonical tools.

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:29.940
We'll draft a manuscript, a very bare-bone sort

00:01:29.940 --> 00:01:32.640
of data descriptor manuscript, and then we have also a

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:35.580
reviewer engine built into this as well.

00:01:35.580 --> 00:01:38.960
And then the final piece is to broadcast this information to the

00:01:39.090 --> 00:01:40.280
masses.

00:01:40.940 --> 00:01:43.660
And so this is just a quick mock-up of what

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:46.100
the portal looks like right now.

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:47.760
We're going to sign in with our at-proto

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:51.760
account, giving everybody universal access to these decentralized identities.

00:01:51.780 --> 00:01:55.380
The first portal that you might get into is this, like

00:01:55.380 --> 00:01:59.000
, upload data type of portal where you're uploading your sequence

00:01:59.050 --> 00:02:02.240
data or images of plants or insects, anything that is kind

00:02:02.240 --> 00:02:05.820
of collected from the scientists doing this sort of work.

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:09.710
And then once you've uploaded your data, which it could

00:02:09.780 --> 00:02:12.520
be, you know, plants, DNA sequence data and the

00:02:12.550 --> 00:02:16.720
like, metadata that helps, we grind that through our analysis

00:02:16.760 --> 00:02:21.270
workflows and essentially give you a readout of the diversity information

00:02:21.340 --> 00:02:22.400
inside of your samples.

00:02:24.400 --> 00:02:27.350
From there, because this is not ultra-complex science

00:02:27.350 --> 00:02:32.070
, I feel confident in taking the use of AI to create

00:02:32.070 --> 00:02:34.300
some draft narratives from these things.

00:02:34.300 --> 00:02:40.360
And so you can imagine this rapid dissemination of work through

00:02:40.360 --> 00:02:42.920
LLMs, where instead of having data products that are

00:02:42.920 --> 00:02:46.780
essentially waiting for analysis, we have a rapid ability to essentially

00:02:46.780 --> 00:02:50.390
communicate this in language that humans tend to agree upon.

00:02:52.580 --> 00:02:55.970
All right, so once the papers are published, what does

00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:56.980
this look like?

00:02:56.980 --> 00:03:00.740
This is just kind of a glimpse into our current imaginative

00:03:00.740 --> 00:03:01.900
process here.

00:03:01.900 --> 00:03:05.280
But we think that AI reviewers and human reviewers are both going

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:06.280
to be required.

00:03:06.280 --> 00:03:09.200
We know AI is going to become, you know, it

00:03:09.200 --> 00:03:11.480
's already a commodity, and so we can review papers with

00:03:11.480 --> 00:03:13.160
the push of a button, essentially.

00:03:13.160 --> 00:03:16.050
But I do truly think we will always need humans in the

00:03:16.050 --> 00:03:18.440
loop who know what these things are and know what they're

00:03:18.440 --> 00:03:18.930
doing.

00:03:18.940 --> 00:03:22.000
And the different categories here, for example, you know,

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:24.700
novelty, we probably want that scored by a human more so

00:03:24.700 --> 00:03:25.540
than a robot.

00:03:25.540 --> 00:03:29.520
So just kind of a glimpse into how we're approaching this

00:03:29.520 --> 00:03:29.810
.

00:03:29.820 --> 00:03:35.480
And so what do you do with all this information?

00:03:35.480 --> 00:03:37.660
So I'm an editor at two scientific journals, and it

00:03:37.660 --> 00:03:40.020
's totally broken, and we can drink beers and pour one

00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.500
out for that broken system.

00:03:42.040 --> 00:03:45.340
And so the next system is this more public one I think

00:03:45.340 --> 00:03:49.120
that could be built on at protocol and one that shows reviews

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:51.490
in a transparent format.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:52.940
You know, we can share these things.

00:03:52.940 --> 00:03:55.000
They're immutable, they're reproducible, and they

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:56.020
can be cited themselves.

00:03:56.020 --> 00:04:00.130
And then further, researchers, they can start to take credit

00:04:00.130 --> 00:04:01.540
for these things.

00:04:01.540 --> 00:04:04.860
And this is a missing part of the scientific discourse that has

00:04:04.860 --> 00:04:07.180
basically completely been missed.

00:04:07.180 --> 00:04:12.760
And so the science that I do, the folks that collect

00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:16.000
these samples, they tend to do these, like, fun

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:18.130
excursions where they go to, like, the California

00:04:18.130 --> 00:04:18.960
coast, for example.

00:04:18.960 --> 00:04:22.780
And so what I'm imagining for something akin to, like

00:04:22.780 --> 00:04:26.030
, the chive eprints or my version of that are

00:04:26.140 --> 00:04:31.010
these interactive story maps that can be automatically generated from these data

00:04:31.010 --> 00:04:31.580
sets.

00:04:31.580 --> 00:04:35.360
And these are these nice digital artifacts that folks can explore,

00:04:35.360 --> 00:04:37.990
and they're interactive, and they're meant to help tell

00:04:37.990 --> 00:04:39.440
the story of this science.

00:04:39.440 --> 00:04:44.840
And then from there, what can we do?

00:04:44.860 --> 00:04:48.300
Well, we can hopefully amplify this stuff through platforms like Blue

00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:48.720
Sky.

00:04:48.720 --> 00:04:51.680
And there's a bunch of different kind of teasers here

00:04:51.680 --> 00:04:55.200
for how this can all be connected, some, including getting

00:04:55.200 --> 00:04:56.660
ahead of the point here.

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:00.100
But you can advertise your review that you completed it on Blue

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:00.550
Sky.

00:05:00.560 --> 00:05:03.020
You can highlight through HypeGen, which we haven't

00:05:03.020 --> 00:05:06.340
talked about here, but Joel Chan was talking about that in

00:05:06.340 --> 00:05:08.900
a previous meeting that I had with him.

00:05:08.900 --> 00:05:12.910
And we have automatic hypothesis generation that can be captured.

00:05:12.920 --> 00:05:15.210
And then also a hat-tipped assemble, which I

00:05:15.210 --> 00:05:15.680
love.

00:05:15.680 --> 00:05:19.790
I'm imagining this could be a way that folks can build

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:24.190
communities and try to gather trails of evidence that folks can then

00:05:24.190 --> 00:05:26.360
pursue with downstream work.

00:05:26.360 --> 00:05:32.410
Further, Matt, so it's very clear that the discourse

00:05:32.410 --> 00:05:34.810
graphs can play a huge role here, right?

00:05:34.820 --> 00:05:38.070
We all do science, and we all appreciate how science is

00:05:38.070 --> 00:05:38.980
conducted.

00:05:39.320 --> 00:05:43.460
And this is the framework that I think can be very useful

00:05:43.460 --> 00:05:46.950
for naturalists because, for example, there's a whole

00:05:47.060 --> 00:05:50.360
lot of ancestral knowledge and, like, local knowledge that doesn

00:05:50.360 --> 00:05:51.320
't exist online.

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:55.380
And I think that a combination of discourse graphs and symbol and

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:58.260
the rails that Proto represents can really capture this.

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:04.540
And so we're leaving the era of traditional publishing.

00:06:04.540 --> 00:06:06.880
We're no longer going to be looking at static PDFs

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:07.820
and Word docs.

00:06:07.820 --> 00:06:09.670
Everything's going to be more universal.

00:06:09.680 --> 00:06:14.220
We're going to have submissions that accept raw data itself instead

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:16.500
of your written Publix projects.

00:06:16.500 --> 00:06:19.420
The AI process is going to be faster.

00:06:19.420 --> 00:06:21.200
It's painfully slow right now.

00:06:21.280 --> 00:06:24.660
It's also going to continue to leverage human experts.

00:06:24.780 --> 00:06:29.170
The output format, you know, dead paywalled text

00:06:29.170 --> 00:06:30.960
is old out with it.

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:34.570
We are more excited about interactive story maps, knowledge graphs that

00:06:34.570 --> 00:06:37.620
are amenable to large-scale ML applications, certainly the

00:06:37.630 --> 00:06:38.360
future.

00:06:38.780 --> 00:06:42.030
And then in terms of data provenance, clearly we have

00:06:42.030 --> 00:06:47.100
a much more connected system here where the decentralized app protocol can

00:06:47.100 --> 00:06:48.740
help link all these things together.

00:06:48.740 --> 00:06:51.530
And folks can get credit for your reviews, your data production

00:06:51.530 --> 00:06:54.010
, your, you know, everything that we agree is required

00:06:54.010 --> 00:06:54.840
for science.

00:06:54.840 --> 00:06:57.320
All right.

00:06:57.320 --> 00:06:58.160
So last slide.

00:06:58.160 --> 00:06:59.260
So the future ahead.

00:06:59.260 --> 00:07:01.070
And I don't know where we jump in this loop,

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:03.400
but let's pretend we're starting at the top here.

00:07:04.420 --> 00:07:05.810
So we're, you know, a bunch of bug nerd

00:07:05.810 --> 00:07:08.310
s, we're running around California, we're collecting butterflies

00:07:08.380 --> 00:07:09.400
and all these things.

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:12.310
And let's say we take those back into the laboratory and

00:07:12.310 --> 00:07:15.110
we look at the DNA and we take pictures of these things

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:15.440
.

00:07:15.440 --> 00:07:18.340
And then we get to the bottom part here where we publish

00:07:18.340 --> 00:07:21.520
them with these sort of little interactive story maps.

00:07:21.520 --> 00:07:24.620
And then from there, we can have these automated hooks to

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:30.440
produce hypotheses from these data sets that folks online and through connections

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:33.030
with Semble, we can eventually get to a point at

00:07:33.030 --> 00:07:35.740
which you would say, aha, time for a field campaign

00:07:35.740 --> 00:07:36.060
2.

00:07:36.060 --> 00:07:36.420
0.

00:07:36.420 --> 00:07:38.880
We're going to pursue this next set of hypotheses.

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:42.740
And in total, I guess I feel that this is the

00:07:42.740 --> 00:07:46.010
scientific loop that is possible if we build this and with the

00:07:46.010 --> 00:07:48.040
community that we're hoping to see.

00:07:48.040 --> 00:07:56.590
Any questions for Sean

00:07:56.590 --> 00:07:57.960
?

00:07:57.960 --> 00:07:58.720
Thank you, Sean.

00:08:01.430 --> 00:08:05.420
Random question.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:07.890
Are you using the IGSNs at all for the

00:08:07.890 --> 00:08:11.420
inner, the geosample numbers identifiers in what

00:08:11.420 --> 00:08:12.280
you're doing?

00:08:12.280 --> 00:08:12.860
Just curious.

00:08:12.860 --> 00:08:13.180
Yeah.

00:08:13.180 --> 00:08:13.550
Yes.

00:08:13.560 --> 00:08:13.920
Cool.

00:08:13.920 --> 00:08:14.580
Awesome.

00:08:14.580 --> 00:08:14.980
Yep.

00:08:14.980 --> 00:08:17.880
Trying to connect in all of the relevant, you know,

00:08:17.880 --> 00:08:20.000
keys from everybody's databases.

00:08:20.000 --> 00:08:20.540
Nice.

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:20.940
Okay.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:23.400
More questions?

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:29.240
Thank you for shouting out discourse graphs.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:31.960
So what kind of schema do you think helps?

00:08:31.960 --> 00:08:35.670
What kind of schema do you think helps put guardrails

00:08:35.670 --> 00:08:40.060
on the generation of the initial manuscript from the data?

00:08:40.060 --> 00:08:42.130
Hmm.

00:08:45.060 --> 00:08:47.950
I guess I want to understand, do you feel like there

00:08:47.950 --> 00:08:51.080
will be too many folks that are able to contribute?

00:08:51.080 --> 00:08:53.610
Or I guess I'm just trying to understand your...

00:08:53.620 --> 00:08:56.420
Yeah, like going from the data analysis to the scientific story

00:08:56.420 --> 00:08:58.900
, like maybe that's where you can plug in discourse graphs

00:08:58.900 --> 00:09:03.160
as well and do this claim-based review the same way

00:09:03.160 --> 00:09:09.820
that like QED, this other AI review program does.

00:09:09.820 --> 00:09:13.470
If you keep the claim structure and each line of evidence as

00:09:13.470 --> 00:09:17.580
something that people can look back to that gets regenerated into

00:09:17.580 --> 00:09:21.680
these different narratives, then maybe it'll be more auditable

00:09:21.680 --> 00:09:22.000
.

00:09:22.000 --> 00:09:22.660
Perfect.

00:09:22.660 --> 00:09:25.840
Yeah, I think integration at multiple points with the tools that

00:09:25.840 --> 00:09:27.780
you're building up is the way to go.

00:09:35.460 --> 00:09:37.100
All right, let's thank Sean again.

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:39.760
And yeah, Alex, feel free to come up.
